<p class="">    <h2>Key Challenges in the RASP Tool Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Complex Integration:</strong> Integrating RASP tools into existing application architectures can be challenging. Many businesses face difficulties in ensuring seamless compatibility, leading to potential disruptions in application performance.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Performance Overhead:</strong> While RASP tools provide real-time protection, they can incur performance overhead. Organizations often grapple with balancing security measures while maintaining optimal application speed and responsiveness.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Limited Visibility:</strong> RASP tools may not always provide comprehensive visibility into application vulnerabilities. This limitation can hinder organizations' ability to effectively monitor application security and respond to threats in real-time.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Simplified Threat Models:</strong> RASP tools often work on predetermined threat models, which may not capture the diverse range of threats faced by modern applications. This simplification can lead to inadequate protection against evolving attack vectors.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Skills Gap:</strong> There is a notable shortage of professionals skilled in deploying and managing RASP solutions. This skills gap can result in inefficient tool utilization and undercapitalization on potential protective benefits.        </li>    </ul>    <h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the RASP Tool Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Increased Adoption of DevSecOps:</strong> As organizations increasingly embrace DevSecOps practices, the demand for integrated security solutions like RASP is expected to rise. This approach encourages embedding security in the development cycle, creating significant opportunities for RASP tool vendors.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Cloud-Native Deve